          <h2>Why <i>Bradyrhizobium japoniucum</i>?</h2>
          <p>Bradyrhizobium japonicum is our bacterium of interest because of its unique ability to form a symbiotic relationship with soybean plants. The bacteria provide the soybean plant with a source of essential nutrients by fixing nitrogen from the atmosphere and then converting it to ammonium for the plant to use. By promoting these symbiotic relationships, soybean plants are able to grow in soils that lack a sufficient source of nitrogen.</p>
          <p>This is significant because a persistent issue in the agricultural industry has been the overuse of nitrogen-enriched fertilizers and the associated consequences of that overuse in the form of pollution. Soybean production in the United States is a booming business and the US is both the world’s leading producer and exporter of soybeans and soybean products. Large-scale pollution from nitrogen enriched fertilizer overuse presents serious issues for local waterways and aquifers that are ill-equipped to process such large amounts of nitrogen, leading to algae blooms and loss of aquatic life</p>
          <p>Allowing farmers the opportunity to greatly reduce or eliminate the the nitrogen-fertilizer use necessary to sustain healthy plant growth and enrich soil in fields used for crop rotation is a significant step in limiting the issues stated above. Therefore our research aimed at developing a better understanding of this symbiotic interaction and the genetic mechanisms by which it is mediated presents important implications for US agriculture as well as other implications within the field of biology.</p>
