          <h2>How does the symbiosis take place?</h2>
          <p>Many of the specific processes by which B. japonicum and the soybean plant undergo symbiosis are largely unknown or not fully understood within the scientific community. However, initial stages of the soybean infection by B. japonicum have been well documented and researched. The soybean plant attracts the bacterium via the release of a specific chemoattractant called an isoflavonoid. The bacteria in the soil then progress towards the roots of the soybean. Once they reach the roots they are captured by lateral root hairs which deform into what are called “Shepherd’s crooks”. The bacteria trapped inside these crooks then begin the process of infection whereby they are taken up inside a specialized organ that forms on the plant roots, unique to the soybean plant, that are referred to as nodules. As this nodule expands, the bacteria then differentiate into bacteroids that are capable of fixing atmospheric nitrogen for the plant to use. By providing the plant with a source of nutrients, the bacteria are afforded protection within the nodule as well as a steady supply of carbon.</p>
          <p>While the study of more complex mechanisms of this infection are outside of the scope of this project; the main questions guiding our research concern two symbiotic genes that mediate the bacterium’s infection of the soybean roots: fegA and ecfs. What we wish to determine is if either fegA or ecfs is the predominant mechanism by which this symbiosis occurs. Additionally, we want to compare how the strains of B. japonicum that we have isolated in the lab will compete with wild-type strains that we obtain and isolate from soil collected from rural farmland, including fields used to cultivate soybeans, surrounding James Madison University.</p>
